I just want to remind you all that Tex is lying about being intersex.
As >>22534879 points out, there are many different kinds of intersexuality. And they have very different physical symptoms.
Texanon claims to not know what kind of intersexuality he has. This is legitimately preposterous.
We know that Tex has intersex genitalia, meaning that he has a 'severe' (for lack of a better word) form of intersexuality. This contrasts with some chromosomal forms of intersexuality which have little to no effect on a person's body, and can go undiscovered for life. Doctors would have noticed Tex's genitalia while he was in the womb. With Tex's parents' permission, doctors would have been able to determine exactly what kind of intersexuality Tex had - if not before birth, then soon after. It is highly likely that Tex's parents would have given permission for these tests because it is medically important information. Different kinds of intersexuality have a profound effect on the body's interaction with certain medications, risks of medical conditions, cancers, etc. It is vital for a parent to know these things.
But okay. Maybe Tex's parents didn't get these tests done, or they did, but they never told Tex the results, leaving him unsure. It doesn't matter, because Tex has been hospitalised multiple times in his life, including as an independent adult. If Texanon couldn't tell the doctors what kind of intersexuality he has, they would have tested him immediately upon entry and told him the results. Again, this is vital medical information, like doing a blood test, there's no way to get around it.

>>28850175

Short answer: maybe, if you're unlucky (you aren't, you already have D cups) or dosing wrong (no way to know how your body would prefer prog administered to maximize growth)

Long answer: probably not

Prog is part of the natural cis female cycle, starting at the first period, long before breast development is anywhere near finished. Prog has been observed to modulate the expression and behavior of estrogen receptors. If I'm remembering correctly, in rabbit models large spikes have been shown to result in a (very) temporary downregulation of estrogen receptors on the surface of breast cells. Our reproductive systems are quite different, but this MAY be an argument in favor of cycling prog, as it also results in a burst of prolactin which makes the tissue more sensitive estrogen after prog levels dip. The best thing to do if you want to maximize breast growth, IMO, is to get all of the growth you can out of just E before staying on prog long term, as everyone's body will respond differently to it. If you want more facial feminization, prog typically accelerates those changes.

Losing weight with a low caloric intake can reduce breast growth. Cardio can increase growth hormone levels and causes the loss of visceral fat. Visceral fat is important for hormone regulation and too much of it can have a negative impact on feminization.

If you don't want to lose muscle, too, just make sure you eat a healthy amount of protein instead of cutting it like the article describes.

If you're trying to lose weight, I suggest you try to retain your muscle until you've lost the fat you want. Losing muscle will reduce your metabolism and make it harder to lose fat in the future.

I feel like I should maybe clarify something, I was assuming you were a hardcore gym rat before. The natural state for any physical body is "use it or lose it". Imagine you're constantly losing a small percentage of your strength every day. Normal activity, like walking down the hall and taking out the trash causes you to build a very small amount of strength. Working out does a lot more. If you did nothing but lay in bed, staring at the ceiling, the loss would stack up quickly and you'd notice it after a few days. Just doing that little bit of housework helps to counteract this a lot. Testosterone made it so the rate that you lose strength at was low. Without male levels of T, the rate you lose strength at will be a lot higher, so you need to do more just to counteract the loss and even more to bulk. If you were already ripped you'd probably notice yourself plateau a bit.

Yeah you have to start somewhere and that's the most hard part. Line up some boxes and start to toss stuff in them. Start with broad categories and put labels on the boxes. Like tools here, toys there, documents elsewhere, etc. Get more boxes when you run out, repeat. Then you can refine the categories like different kinds of tools or documents to sort. Change things up when you realize a certain type of organisation isn't helpful.
In the hospital I was legit sent home to get all the documents I could find, put them in a box and come back. Just bring everything I could find. Then I had the task to sort this shit out with the help of social workers in order to find the most recent bills to pay, make a folder with important stuff and throw out the trash. There were bank statements, old bills, payrolls, etc. spanning almost a decade to sort out.
But you can do it bro. You don't have to do it all at once. Take your time.

The Scottish Gender Recognition Act (GRA) reform bill is due to be voted on today after 6 years of debates and two public consultations. If the bill passed the GRA will be reformed to allow transgender people to obtain a Gender Recognition Certificate without the approval of a medical board. A GRC changes the sex on your birth certificate (which is not a valid form of ID) so that the owner can have medical privacy and get married and die without being outed on public records.

We're currently at stage 3 of the parliamentary process, which is where people submit, debate and vote on amendments to the reform before they vote on it. The vote has been delayed until today because TERFs and Tories have been filibustering to buy time until next year, forcing the vote to happen after parliament goes on Christmas break (Friday). The vote will likely happen late this evening.

Stage 3 is confusing and hard to keep track of, so I'll be updating this thread with the amendments being voted on, if they pass or fail and what that means as well as getting everyone up to date on what's happened so far.

Good luck Scotanons. If you find this thread useful, please bump it in-between updates.

>>28825649
>probably because (ive noticed this with myself) we feel empathy by imagining the other party is literally us

Correct, although everyone does this to some extent. When you know nothing about what another person thinks, instead of assuming they're braindead you instead make conscious and unconscious assumptions that they will be mostly-identical to everyone you've met previously (until proven otherwise). Because the more similar they are to you, the easier it is to "empathize"

The simplest example is sharing your favorite show or food with a friend, and being incredulous or baffled that they don't like it. Or making references they don't get. You used yourself and your own mind to serve as a base model.

This is fine for most day-to-day applications, as it lets you assume every random person you meet on the street will speak the same language and have the same desires and fears.

But at its worst, it can cause a lifetime of social dysfunction if your internal "base model" of humanity is warped

From infancy, parents serve as our base example for how adults operate, and if they're flawed then those flaws can give us a bad definition of normal human behavior. If your parents are hypercritical, then you might grow up falsely assuming everyone else scrutinizing you just as badly.

>i wonder why autists have object empathy at a higher rate than NTs.

Because you can "know" what an object is thinking and never be wrong, or have the stress of being contradicted. An object's "feelings" are entirely per-defined and predictable. Unlike real people who have their own agency, and will create a sense of chaos by acting or thinking independently. You can have stuffed animals that always "get along with each other", but your real-life friends won't

Goal of the thread: Think of something you are grateful for. Feel free to share it with us, but no pressure!
Daily goals can be repeated. Remember to keep score, it can only go up!

>What is this thread for?
Getting better is hard, and sucks. A lot. It does not get easier doing it alone.
Share resources and experiences with combating depression, anxiety, personal issues, achieving or maintaining a healthy weight, etc.
>Why is this thread /lgbt/?
Struggles with mental and physical health are an indisputable part of /lgbt/ life, be it from dysphoria, social pressure, heartbreak, or just unfortunate lifestyle choices.
>Notes to consider:
Please be civil. Shame is your greatest enemy in fighting urges of self abuse (be it sh, drugs, or just self deprecation). Relapsing into bad and unhealthy habits is to be expected, the goal is to increase the average amount of time it takes between relapses. Any improvement is a victory no matter how small. Your worth and right to get better are non-negotiable. And most importantly:
WE ARE NOT THERAPISTS, WE DON'T REPLACE MEDICATION
>Note on advice
Generic advice won't necessarily help you in particular, but for those it does it is an essential foundation to build future progress on, not a miracle cure. Do not underestimate the effects subtle changes to your lifestyle can have. Try first, keep us posted on your progress, build from there.

I think one thing that could be added that's helped me a ton is encouraging journaling your memories and feelings about them. I found it helped me immensely in both recovering from and uncovering old trauma I was still carrying around, as well as feel more connected to myself as a person in my own right by giving me a private, safe place to put my inner voice into outer words.
It can be weird to start, but a prompt that usually helps is to try to write as much detail as you can recall about how you got from being born, to being where you are now. It will jump around a lot and have a lot of holes to start with, but it was amazing just how much myself and others have been able to remember about ourselves from just asking yourself to bother remembering it. Even a year later I'm not great at remembering what age things actually happened at, but I've been able to carve out a very solid timeline even for my first 4-5 years of life, and I'm getting there for the next 10-15 slowly but surely, and that's helped me feel a lot more real and capable of handling things like self improvement, because I know the self I want to improve for better.

>>28854096
>That went straight into the book, don't you worry.
Oh, you're making a book? Cool! I guess my last advice on it before I sleep would be how to set one up.

If you want it to be private, you can use an encrypted messaging app like signal or element. These work on both PC and phone with the same account and access to message history. Signal needs a phone number to work, and element only needs an email and password.
Both have character limits though, which can be a problem if your entries start getting very long (which they will after a while, since you're expressing, at the least, entire years in all their detail into text), and some people don't like the chatroom format for journals at all. If that's a problem, skiff is also good as an encrypted version of google docs and you can write as much as you want and format it however you like. This also works on anything with a web browser, and has a mobile app.

As my journal gets longer and more detailed, I've found that using a chat for quickly writing down things, where ever I happen to be, as I remember them is best, and then consolidating things into a timeline on a proper document works for me. The chatroom format can get a bit unwieldy when you have hundreds of various entries, all hundreds to thousands of words long and jumping to different ages and eras all the time.

Good luck to anyone who takes on journaling as a healing practice. It can be very intense and you may need a hug or other support as you process everything that's happened to you. Don't be afraid to reach out to a friend or family member if you have one you trust or can rely on, or you can post online somewhere.

>>28854147
It's important to remember that you picked up a habit for a reason, and that substance use isn't a inherently evil thing. You're not broken for being addicted to anything, rather the addiction is used to soothe something else that makes you feel unable to exist with yourself as is.

it's super common, but the severity depends on how well your self esteem is doing. It is super normal to overthink things, you are far from alone. you already isolated the thing that is going awry, and you probably already catch yourself doing it, right?
